---
import Layout from "@/layouts/main.astro";

const title = "Memory Span & Visuospatial Science | CogniArena";
const description = "Understand visuospatial chunking limits, Miller's Law equations, short-term working memory capacity, and pattern recognition.";
const canonicalUrl = "https://cogniarena.com/learn/memory-test";

const schemaJson = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "Article",
  "headline": "Science of Visuospatial Recall, Working Memory, and Miller's Law Limits",
  "description": "Analyze chunking tactics, Short-term memory limits, and cognitive decay rates.",
  "publisher": {
    "@type": "Organization",
    "name": "CogniArena"
  }
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonicalUrl={canonicalUrl} schemaJson={schemaJson}>
  <div class="flex flex-col gap-12 w-full max-w-3xl mx-auto">
    <header class="flex flex-col gap-3">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-2 text-xs font-mono uppercase tracking-widest text-accent">
        <span>Learning Center</span>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <span>Pillar Page</span>
      </div>
      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground animate-fade-in">
        Memory Science & Chunking Limits
      </h1>
      <p class="text-muted dark:text-muted text-sm md:text-base leading-relaxed">
        Investigating prefrontal working memory limits, sensory memory decay rates, and spatial chunking strategies.
      </p>
    </header>

    <section class="flex flex-col gap-10 border-t border-card-border pt-10">
      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">1. Miller's Law and Working Memory Capacity</h2>
        <p class="text-muted dark:text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
          Formulated by cognitive psychologist George Miller in 1956, Miller's Law states that the number of objects an average human can hold in working memory is 7 &plusmn; 2. This limit applies to immediate recall tasks (sensory buffer registers) and is governed by prefrontal cortical circuit sizes.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">2. Visuospatial Chunking Strategies</h2>
        <p class="text-muted dark:text-muted text-sm leading-relaxed">
          High-performance memory scores are achieved by chunking individual items into consolidated logical units. In a spatial grid test, this involves grouping coordinate sequences into visual lines, polygons, or motion trajectories, mapping multiple variables into a single conceptual unit.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="flex flex-col gap-4">
        <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground tracking-tight">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
        <div class="flex flex-col gap-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-foreground font-bold mb-1">Can working memory span be permanently increased?</h4>
            <p class="text-muted dark:text-muted">While absolute working memory capacity is highly correlated with genetics, you can significantly optimize effective recall through chunking techniques and spatial associations.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <h4 class="text-foreground font-bold mb-1">What is the difference between short-term and working memory?</h4>
            <p class="text-muted dark:text-muted">Short-term memory refers strictly to the passive storage of information, while working memory involves both storage and active manipulation of those data points.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </section>
  </div>
</Layout>
